{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Rhode Island v. Massachusetts |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate=February 21 |DecideYear=1838 |FullName=The State of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, Complainants v. The Commonwealth of Massachusetts, Defendant |USVol=37 |USPage=657 |ParallelCitations=12 [[Richard Peters (reporter)|Pet.]] 657; 9 [[L. Ed.]] 1233; 1838 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 372 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding=Supreme Court has original jurisdiction over a suit by one state against another over their shared border |SCOTUS=1838-1841 |Majority= |JoinMajority= |Dissent=Taney |NotParticipating=Story |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Rhode Island v. Massachusetts''''', 37 U.S. (12 Pet.) 657 (1838), was a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case in which the Court asserted its [[original jurisdiction]] over a suit in [[Equity (law)|equity]] by one state against another over their shared border. The case involved a boundary dispute between [[Massachusetts]] and [[Rhode Island]] dating back to colonial times. [[Daniel Webster]] was involved in the case representing Massachusetts.
==External links== * {{caselaw source | case = ''Rhode Island v. Massachusetts'', {{Ussc|37|657|1838|Pet.|12|el=no}} | findlaw = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/37/657.html | justia =https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/37/657/ | loc =http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep037/usrep037657/usrep037657.pdf | openjurist =https://openjurist.org/37/us/657 }}
[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]] [[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Taney Court]] [[Category:United States Supreme Court original jurisdiction cases]] [[Category:Property law in the United States]] [[Category:1838 in United States case law]] [[Category:Internal territorial disputes of the United States]] [[Category:Legal history of Massachusetts]] [[Category:Borders of Massachusetts]] [[Category:Legal history of Rhode Island]] [[Category:Borders of Rhode Island]] [[Category:1838 in Massachusetts]] [[Category:1838 in Rhode Island]]

In [[collective bargaining]], '''surface bargaining''' is a strategy in which one of the parties "merely goes through the motions," with no intention of reaching an agreement.{{sfn|Caisley|2007|page=170}}{{sfn|Carrell|Heavrin|2001|page=159}} In this regard, it is a form of [[bad faith]] bargaining.{{sfn|Caisley|2007|page=170}}

Distinguishing surface bargaining from [[good faith]] bargaining is extremely difficult.{{sfn|Emerson|2009|page=580}} The entire history of the negotiations must be assessed, including the party's intent, efforts made toward reaching an agreement, and any behavior which may be seen as inhibiting the bargaining process.{{sfn|Caisley|2007|page=171}}{{sfn|Morris|Hardin|LaVaute|O'Reilly|1992|pages=616-632}} Surface bargaining tactics may include making proposals the other party could never accept, taking inflexible or unreasonable stands on issues, and/or refusing to offer alternatives to proposals.{{sfn|Morris|Hardin|LaVaute|O'Reilly|1992|pages=616-632}}{{sfn|Holley|Jennings|Wolters|2009|page=272}} Reneging on agreements already reached during the collective bargaining process, raising new issues late in the negotiations, or failing to follow generally accepted procedures for collective bargaining may also be seen as signs of surface bargaining.{{sfn|Forsyth|Stewart|page=137}}

Based upon the "totality" of a party's actions during collective bargaining, surface bargaining may be found if there was a purposeful effort to avoid or frustrate mutual agreement.{{sfn|Morris|Hardin|LaVaute|O'Reilly|1992|pages=616-632}}  Under U.S. law, it is an [[Unfair labor practice]] and a breach of the duty to bargain in good faith.{{sfn|Morris|Hardin|LaVaute|O'Reilly|1992|pages=616-632}}

Surface bargaining is barred under the labor law of many countries. Federal and provincial Canadian labor law bars surface bargaining, and Canadian courts have held that the test for determining surface bargaining is to look at the totality of the negotiations.{{sfn|Willes|1990|page=70}} In New Zealand, surface bargaining is a violation of the [[Employment Relations Act 2000]] (as amended).{{sfn|Rudman|2009|page=102}} A "Code of Good Faith" promulgated by the Employment Relations Authority supplements the legal statute, however, and lays out a number of rules for good faith bargaining.{{sfn|Forsyth|Stewart|page=137}} In the United States, surface bargaining constitutes an [[unfair labor practice]] under the [[National Labor Relations Act]].{{sfn|Morris|Hardin|LaVaute|O'Reilly|1992|pages=616-632}}{{sfn|Voos|1994|page=12}} American courts have held that "hard bargaining" (taking a firmly held and well-explained position), failing to make a concession, and/or failing to reach an agreement do not constitute surface bargaining under federal labor law.{{sfn|Twomey|2010|page=168}} Additional evidence, such as away-from-the-table statements or behavior, is needed to prove surface bargaining in the U.S.{{sfn|Twomey|2010|page=168}}

